<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06285003 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06285003 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  COMPUTER; SOFTWARE; EQUIPMENT; COMPANY; EARNINGS; INCREASE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Microsoft Corp., the world's largest producer of personal computer software,reported record profits and sales for its first fiscal quarter, creditingstrong demand for its operating systems.;   Profits for the quarter endedSept. 30 were $144 million, or 75 cents a share, up 64 percent from $87.6million, or 47 cents a share, for the year-earlier period. First-quarter saleswere $580.5 million, up 57 percent from the $369.4 million reported a yearearlier.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  MICROSOFT POSTS RECORD PROFITS  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Earnings  </MEMO><TEXT>     Microsoft has not had a decline in quarterly profits or sales since itsstock went public in March 1986.;   Its stock hit a 52-week high of $89.50 onWednesday on belief that earnings would be strong, then climbed Thursday toclose at $89.75.;   Frank Gaudette, Microsoft senior vice president and chieffinancial officer, said the results reflect continued strong demand for thecompany's MS-DOS 5.0 operating system and Windows 3.0 operating environment.The programs provide the internal instructions for IBM-compatible personalcomputers that allow them to run other programs.;   Since Windows 3.0 wasintroduced in May 1990, more than 6 million copies have been distributedworldwide. More than 130 computer equipment manufacturers have licensedWindows, and more than 1,000 software applications have been written to workwith the program, Microsoft said.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Redmond, Wash.  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911011  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  October  </MONTH><PG.COL>  17E  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  210  </WORD.CT><DAT